{
  "verdict": "vulnerable",
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "vulnerabilities": [
    {
      "type": "Broken AMM invariant (incorrect constant-product check) enables near-free draining of reserves",
      "severity": "critical",
      "vulnerable_lines": [87, 88, 91, 92],
      "location": "exchangeCredentials()",
      "explanation": "The swap invariant check is mathematically wrong due to inconsistent scaling constants. The code scales balances by 10000 (LN-87, LN-88) but compares against reserves scaled by (1000 ** 2) (LN-92). This makes the invariant ~100x weaker than intended (ignoring fees, it effectively allows balance0*balance1 to drop to reserve0*reserve1/100). As a result, an attacker can withdraw a very large amount of one token while providing only a dust amount of the other token to satisfy the nonzero-input requirement, draining the pool at extremely favorable prices.",
      "attack_scenario": "Assume reserves are 1000 token0 and 1000 token1.\n1) Attacker transfers 1 token1 directly to the contract address (so post-swap amount1In will be 1).\n2) Attacker calls exchangeCredentials(amount0Out=900, amount1Out=0, to=attacker, record=0x).\n3) Contract sends 900 token0 to attacker (LN-66).\n4) Post-transfer balances are ~100 token0 and 1001 token1; amount1In is computed as 1 (LN-77 to LN-84).\n5) The weakened invariant (LN-91 to LN-92) passes, so the swap succeeds.\nResult: attacker pays 1 token1 to receive 900 token0, repeating to drain token0 reserves.",
      "suggested_fix": "Fix the invariant scaling to be consistent.\n- If using 10000 as the multiplier, require:\n  balance0Adjusted * balance1Adjusted >= uint256(_reserve0) * uint256(_reserve1) * (10000 ** 2)\n- Alternatively, change adjusted balances to use 1000 and keep (1000 ** 2).\nAlso ensure the fee math matches the chosen basis points (e.g., Uniswap V2 uses 1000 with fee 3 => subtract amountIn*3). Add tests that verify correct pricing and that large withdrawals require proportional inputs."
    }
  ],
  "overall_explanation": "The contract’s swap safety relies on a constant-product invariant, but the invariant is implemented with inconsistent scaling (10000 on the left, 1000^2 on the right). This makes the check far too permissive and allows any user to drain most of one reserve by supplying only a minimal amount of the other token, causing severe loss of funds for liquidity held by the contract."
}
